moondine 27-Jan-21 05:25 PM
Here's a quote
There are 3 possible situations. Lets assume that the object emits light, thats the most easy situation the object can be in. And this assumption does not violate the things we could or could not see, so… It passes above us, from left to right or reverse. Parallel from where we are standing. Then we see a fast moving object, emitting the light it gives. In practice we see the object where it was when it emitted the light we see. In reality it is ahead of this position. The object flies in our direction. In that case we see a fierce blue light or even light in the ultra violet or even higher regions like gamma rays when it is very close to the speed of light. Because what we know as the dopplereffect the frequency of the light is compressed and so the light spectrum is much brighter than emitted. The object flies away from us. Then the light shifts to the (infra)red or even longer frequencies. When the object comes close to the light speed the emitted light is so stretched that we don’t see it anymore. With optical instruments, or radio receivers for very long wavelengths it can still be ‘seen’ of course. Like the microwave background radiation, once gammaray, now in the range of radiowaves, 3° Kelvin. (edited)
